00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:04.630
So before we jump in,
for those who don't know,

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:06.460
please tell us a little
bit about the show,

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:07.280
"The Band's Visit."

00:03:10.937 --> 00:03:12.020
ITAMAR MOSES: Yeah, I'll--

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:12.220
OK.

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:14.740
So "The Band's Visit," which
is based on an Israeli film

00:03:14.740 --> 00:03:17.410
from about 10 years
ago, of the same name,

00:03:17.410 --> 00:03:22.409
is the story of an Egyptian
police orchestra that comes

00:03:22.409 --> 00:03:23.575
to Israel to give a concert.

00:03:23.575 --> 00:03:28.120
But due to miscommunication
at the bus station,

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:30.160
instead of going to
the city of Petah Tikva

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:31.660
that they're supposed
to go to, they

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:34.780
end up in a tiny
village in the middle

00:03:34.780 --> 00:03:37.390
of nowhere with a similar name.

00:03:37.390 --> 00:03:38.950
And there's no
more transportation

00:03:38.950 --> 00:03:41.230
for the rest of the night,
so they're stranded there

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:43.940
and they get taken
in by the locals.

00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:46.330
And the story is just
about what happens

00:03:46.330 --> 00:03:48.920
over the course
of that one night.

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:51.760
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Great.

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:54.320
So it started as a film.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:58.000
What made you guys want to
adapt this into a musical?

00:03:58.000 --> 00:03:59.450
What was that process like?

00:03:59.450 --> 00:04:01.270
DAVID YAZBEK: Well,
it was presented to us

00:04:01.270 --> 00:04:03.910
by our producer,
Orin Wolf, who had

00:04:03.910 --> 00:04:07.607
the kind of daunting
and maybe insane idea

00:04:07.607 --> 00:04:09.190
that the movie could
become a musical.

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:14.900
And it took a while
to sort of see that.

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:15.980
And then it just--

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:17.750
for me, at least, it clicked.

00:04:17.750 --> 00:04:19.910
Oh, this could really
be interesting.

00:04:19.910 --> 00:04:23.450
And then we were off
to the races slowly.

00:04:23.450 --> 00:04:25.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:25.030 --> 00:04:27.010
DAVID CROMER: Orin was
saying it-- is this on?

00:04:27.010 --> 00:04:27.310
DAVID YAZBEK: Yeah.

00:04:27.310 --> 00:04:27.820
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Yeah.

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:28.400
DAVID CROMER: Orin was saying--

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:31.160
Orin Wolf, again, our lead
producer had had this idea,

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:33.542
and went around to a
lot of people saying,

00:04:33.542 --> 00:04:35.000
I want to make this
into a musical.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.086
And people kept saying,
oh, I don't see it.

00:04:37.086 --> 00:04:37.710
I don't see it.

00:04:37.710 --> 00:04:38.334
I don't see it.

00:04:38.334 --> 00:04:40.490
And usually, if three people
tell you you're drunk,

00:04:40.490 --> 00:04:41.570
you should lie down.

00:04:41.570 --> 00:04:43.760
But he didn't do that.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:46.270
And he kept-- and he went--

00:04:46.270 --> 00:04:49.040
and so he eventually
found writers

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:53.630
who saw it, who could see
it, and had an idea for it.

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:57.470
And it's just-- it's sort of
proof that a lot of things

00:04:57.470 --> 00:04:59.480
might not immediately
seem like a good idea,

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:03.920
but it's about what you see in
it, and it is about execution.

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:05.230
You know, any idea's workable--

00:05:05.230 --> 00:05:07.280
DAVID YAZBEK: Not killing
someone type of execution.

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:07.420
DAVID CROMER: Yeah.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:08.210
DAVID YAZBEK: But
doing something.

00:05:08.210 --> 00:05:10.720
DAVID CROMER: Well, just
the execution of an idea.

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:11.660
I thought that was--

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:13.220
I mean, I came in
relatively late,

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:15.680
so I'm speaking about
what transpired before.

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:17.832
But from the
outside, it appears--

00:05:17.832 --> 00:05:19.290
this is the composer,
David Yazbek.

00:05:19.290 --> 00:05:20.581
DAVID YAZBEK: I'm the composer.

00:05:20.581 --> 00:05:21.990
This is the writer,
Itamar Moses,

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:23.073
and this is the director--

00:05:23.073 --> 00:05:23.540
DAVID CROMER: And
I'm the director.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:24.748
DAVID YAZBEK: --David Cromer.

00:05:24.748 --> 00:05:25.380
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:25.595 --> 00:05:26.720
DAVID CROMER: And so, yeah.

00:05:26.720 --> 00:05:28.280
So I just wanted
to make that point

00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:32.270
that it seemed like it did
not immediately adapt itself

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:33.770
to a musical, and
these guys managed

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:37.876
to find a really beautiful way
to adapt it into a musical.

00:05:37.876 --> 00:05:38.750
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Yeah.

00:05:38.750 --> 00:05:40.500
Let's talk a little
bit about that vision.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:42.590
So when you were--
did you feel like you

00:05:42.590 --> 00:05:46.040
had to stay true to the
film when you were writing

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:47.675
the book and the music?

00:05:47.675 --> 00:05:50.420
ITAMAR MOSES: I
mean, yes and no.

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:53.750
Sometimes when something is
being adapted from source

00:05:53.750 --> 00:05:56.120
material, if it's source
material that everybody knows--

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:58.174
some sort of beloved,
hugely famous movie--

00:05:58.174 --> 00:05:59.840
then there's fan
service you have to do.

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:01.880
We didn't have to worry
about it in that sense

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:05.900
because the movie was sort of
an art house cult niche hit.

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:08.360
Except in Israel, where
it's one of the biggest

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:09.889
hits of all time.

00:06:09.889 --> 00:06:11.930
But everywhere else, it's
sort of like, oh, yeah,

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:13.946
I heard about that movie.

00:06:13.946 --> 00:06:16.070
So we didn't have to stay
true to it in that sense.

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:18.980
It was just because
we loved the spirit

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:22.400
of the movie and
the tone it created

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:24.920
and the characters
and the story.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:29.615
So we did want to
stay true to it.

00:06:29.615 --> 00:06:30.990
There are things
you have-- there

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:34.040
are things you have to take into
account when you move from film

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:34.760
to stage.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:37.770
You rely more on dialogue than
on images, stuff like that.

00:06:37.770 --> 00:06:39.965
But we always wanted to--

00:06:39.965 --> 00:06:41.840
we didn't want to do
one of those adaptations

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:43.339
where it was like,
well, why did you

00:06:43.339 --> 00:06:45.230
even use that source material?

00:06:45.230 --> 00:06:46.640
You know, it's sort of--

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:50.420
we wanted to see if we could
take the sort of flickering

00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:54.350
candle flame of
this delicate story

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:58.500
and transfer it to this other
medium without it going out.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:02.840
So yeah, we wanted to, but
in a very non-cynical way.

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:04.520
We felt bound to
the source material.

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:07.160
DAVID CROMER: And I was always
happy to reference to the film.

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.510
I never ran from it,
like, well, we've

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:09.900
got to do something
different than the film.

00:07:09.900 --> 00:07:11.000
I never, ever felt that.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.330
I wanted to-- it was a fantas--
it was a very rich vein

00:07:14.330 --> 00:07:16.139
to draw from.

00:07:16.139 --> 00:07:18.680
MICHAEL SHAYAN: I would love to
speak with the cast and see--

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:22.300
had any of you have
seen the film prior to--

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:23.337
yeah?

00:07:23.337 --> 00:07:24.170
Did you look to it--

00:07:24.170 --> 00:07:25.880
I mean, I can imagine
that you would

00:07:25.880 --> 00:07:27.980
want to create your
own interpretation

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:30.710
of the characters, so
what's that balance?

00:07:30.710 --> 00:07:31.980
How do you approach that?

00:07:35.244 --> 00:07:36.327
JONATHAN RAVIV: All right.

00:07:36.327 --> 00:07:37.776
I'll go.

00:07:37.776 --> 00:07:41.090
So what's lovely
for me is my parents

00:07:41.090 --> 00:07:44.940
are actually Israeli, so I
was familiar with the film.

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:49.340
As Itamar said, it's
very popular in Israel.

00:07:49.340 --> 00:07:52.250
And my character
specifically was actually

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:53.900
more developed in this.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:08:00.470
I play Sammy, who has an affair
with Katrina's character, Dina.

00:08:00.470 --> 00:08:02.600
And that was
fleshed out more, so

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:05.662
that was exciting to
be able to do something

00:08:05.662 --> 00:08:07.370
with a character that
wasn't fleshed out.

00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:11.600
But to answer your question,
I mean, yes, the film

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:15.310
was really helpful to
watch and to take from,

00:08:15.310 --> 00:08:18.764
as Cromer suggested.

00:08:18.764 --> 00:08:19.930
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Yeah, great.

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:22.390
David, a question for you.

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:24.940
When you were writing
the music, how

00:08:24.940 --> 00:08:27.370
do you figure out what
songs you want to write,

00:08:27.370 --> 00:08:29.395
where they're going to go?

00:08:29.395 --> 00:08:32.110
You obviously are
working with Itamar here,

00:08:32.110 --> 00:08:34.240
but what's that process like?

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:35.289
And how do you--

00:08:35.289 --> 00:08:36.490
I mean, I watched the film.

00:08:36.490 --> 00:08:38.409
I'm like, where's
the music, you know?

00:08:38.409 --> 00:08:40.350
What's your process
for figuring that out?

00:08:40.350 --> 00:08:43.470
DAVID YAZBEK: Well, it's
different for every show.

00:08:43.470 --> 00:08:49.060
This was my fourth show
that actually got completed.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:54.610
With this one, there
was a full script

00:08:54.610 --> 00:08:58.587
that Itamar had
adapted from the movie,

00:08:58.587 --> 00:08:59.920
and I had only written one song.

00:08:59.920 --> 00:09:02.260
This was when we did
our first reading.

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:06.280
After that script was done,
songs suggested themselves

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:09.890
from the story in the
script, some of the lines

00:09:09.890 --> 00:09:11.390
in the script.

00:09:11.390 --> 00:09:12.950
Itamar and I did
a lot of talking

00:09:12.950 --> 00:09:21.080
about what should be sung and
not sung, and a year later,

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:23.954
changed 50% of that.

00:09:23.954 --> 00:09:25.370
That doesn't work,
this does work.

00:09:25.370 --> 00:09:27.700
Let's do this instead.

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:29.550
You're reaching to
grab the mic from me?

00:09:29.550 --> 00:09:31.107
ITAMAR MOSES: Yeah,
but it just seems

00:09:31.107 --> 00:09:32.690
like so much more
of a hostile gesture

00:09:32.690 --> 00:09:37.960
than I meant it, just because
there's microphone scarcity.

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:40.340
Yeah, no, a verb
that we use a lot--

00:09:40.340 --> 00:09:41.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:44.810
--a verb that we use a lot
to describe that process

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:46.340
is cannibalize.

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:48.740
You create-- the book writer
creates script material,

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:52.220
and then you want it to
suggest songs in such a way

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:55.970
that a composer can cannibalize
dialogue or monologues,

00:09:55.970 --> 00:09:57.430
or just story moments.

00:09:57.430 --> 00:10:00.110
DAVID YAZBEK: So
sometimes, I will say, oh,

00:10:00.110 --> 00:10:04.580
that scene could become
a song, or that section

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:05.360
can become a song.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:08.414
And other times, I'll say--

00:10:08.414 --> 00:10:09.830
if there's nothing
to cannibalize,

00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:12.830
but there's an idea for a
song, a lot of the time,

00:10:12.830 --> 00:10:13.950
I'll say to--

00:10:13.950 --> 00:10:16.040
I said to Itamar,
could you write

00:10:16.040 --> 00:10:17.360
me something to cannibalize?

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:21.040
Literally, a monologue or
a little scene or something

00:10:21.040 --> 00:10:21.540
like that.

00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:26.420
Or just have long conversations
which were probably very

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:29.810
frustrating for him, where I
would just be, yeah, but what--

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:30.740
but why should they--

00:10:30.740 --> 00:10:32.210
why would you want-- why?

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:34.190
And then maybe one sentence--

00:10:34.190 --> 00:10:35.060
ITAMAR MOSES: My phone
would just be on speaker

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:36.180
and I'd be like, uh-huh, uh-huh.

00:10:36.180 --> 00:10:36.560
DAVID YAZBEK: Yeah.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:37.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:38.860
Yeah, he'd be frying an egg.

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:41.985
And one sentence would come out
and I'd be like, oh, I see now.

00:10:41.985 --> 00:10:43.610
ITAMAR MOSES: It's
interesting actually

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:45.450
because a lot of times--

00:10:45.450 --> 00:10:48.650
and I've worked on a
couple of musicals also.

00:10:48.650 --> 00:10:53.180
This movie and the script
for the movie is very spare,

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:53.890
and a lot is--

00:10:53.890 --> 00:10:56.720
there's very little-- I think
my first draft of the adaptation

00:10:56.720 --> 00:11:00.034
was literally, I want to
say, 23 or 24 pages long.

00:11:00.034 --> 00:11:02.450
If you actually put all the
dialogue in the film in order,

00:11:02.450 --> 00:11:04.830
there's not much of it.

00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:07.130
And so what that
means-- one thing

00:11:07.130 --> 00:11:10.880
that means is that a lot
of things are left unsaid,

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:15.500
which is great, but it doesn't
give a lot for the composer

00:11:15.500 --> 00:11:17.330
to springboard off of.

00:11:17.330 --> 00:11:21.069
So in another kind of a
script, there might already

00:11:21.069 --> 00:11:23.360
be a very explicit monologue,
where the character talks

00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:24.818
about exactly what
they're feeling,

00:11:24.818 --> 00:11:26.750
and the composer turns
that into a song.

00:11:26.750 --> 00:11:28.332
In "Band's Visit,"
in my first draft,

00:11:28.332 --> 00:11:30.290
those speeches weren't
there because that's not

00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:33.620
how these people talk, and
not the tone of this piece.

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:36.530
DAVID YAZBEK: And that was
great for me, as a songwriter,

00:11:36.530 --> 00:11:41.540
because the songs in this
show, a lot of them, are--

00:11:41.540 --> 00:11:44.240
they don't feel like
they're assignments

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:47.540
imposed by a script, you know?

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:49.640
They come out of
character and they

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:51.800
come from a very deep
place because of that.

00:11:51.800 --> 00:11:54.200
So I'm able to sort of--

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:57.170
we'll talk about, what
does this character like?

00:11:57.170 --> 00:11:58.010
What is he thinking?

00:11:58.010 --> 00:11:59.990
The movie gives us hints.

00:11:59.990 --> 00:12:04.070
And I can actually write from
the heart in a much deeper way

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:06.590
than I've been able
to in other shows.

00:12:06.590 --> 00:12:09.195
So I enjoyed the process.

00:12:09.195 --> 00:12:10.070
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Yeah.

00:12:10.070 --> 00:12:11.611
I mean, the music
is really beautiful

00:12:11.611 --> 00:12:16.400
and there are, obviously,
Arabic undertones,

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:19.400
Israeli, Egyptian undertones.

00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:22.009
Had you had experiences
with Arabic music before?

00:12:22.009 --> 00:12:22.800
DAVID YAZBEK: Yeah.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:24.500
There's a story
that, now that we're

00:12:24.500 --> 00:12:27.560
in publicity mode for the
show, I've told a lot.

00:12:27.560 --> 00:12:30.350
But I like telling it.

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:35.120
My tastes in music are very
eclectic and always have been.

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:40.220
And my father is
Lebanese-American,

00:12:40.220 --> 00:12:42.440
first generation.

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:46.150
But never-- you know, we had
"Kiss Me Kate" and "The Music

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:46.995
Man," you know?

00:12:46.995 --> 00:12:52.130
Our album collection was that
and classical stuff, basically.

00:12:52.130 --> 00:12:54.740
But he took me to Lebanon
to visit his father

00:12:54.740 --> 00:12:56.270
when I was about seven.

00:12:56.270 --> 00:12:58.670
We were in the taxi
from the airport.

00:12:58.670 --> 00:13:03.800
The taxi driver had
music on the radio.

00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:06.004
And I have a sense memory of it.

00:13:06.004 --> 00:13:06.920
The windows were open.

00:13:06.920 --> 00:13:10.640
It was hot air
blasting in, and there

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:12.530
was this music on the radio.

00:13:12.530 --> 00:13:16.520
And I asked my father to ask
the cab driver in Arabic what

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:17.420
was playing.

00:13:17.420 --> 00:13:20.870
It turns out, it
was Umm Kulthum,

00:13:20.870 --> 00:13:24.260
who's mentioned in a song
as sort of a central--

00:13:24.260 --> 00:13:27.500
who was the Frank Sinatra of--

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:29.030
she was more
popular than Sinatra

00:13:29.030 --> 00:13:32.840
at the time, Middle
Eastern singer.

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:35.570
And the way the orchestra
sounded and this--

00:13:35.570 --> 00:13:39.440
I didn't know it at the time,
but these weird microtones,

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:41.270
and the way she was singing.

00:13:41.270 --> 00:13:42.840
And it all was very--

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:44.600
made a big impression on me.

00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:46.752
So since then, I've
been open to it.

00:13:46.752 --> 00:13:48.710
I've been to a lot of
different kinds of music.

00:13:48.710 --> 00:13:53.240
Pretty much everything except
Peking opera, let's say.

00:13:53.240 --> 00:13:56.520
There's always something
that you just can't get.

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:57.500
But it--

00:13:57.500 --> 00:13:58.790
ITAMAR MOSES: You should
challenge yourself and make

00:13:58.790 --> 00:13:59.330
that your next project.

00:13:59.330 --> 00:13:59.870
DAVID YAZBEK: Well, I did.

00:13:59.870 --> 00:14:02.030
I went-- I was trying
to write a Bruce Lee

00:14:02.030 --> 00:14:04.130
musical a few years ago.

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:06.710
But-- no, I really was.

00:14:06.710 --> 00:14:08.125
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:08.125 --> 00:14:10.000
ITAMAR MOSES: Everyone's
like, is that a bit?

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.820
DAVID YAZBEK: No, it's
not a-- this isn't a bit.

00:14:12.820 --> 00:14:15.520
But anyway, so I was open to it.

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:18.790
And then in the '80s, there
was kind of this world music,

00:14:18.790 --> 00:14:22.021
this flourishing of
world music that--

00:14:22.021 --> 00:14:23.770
I guess the record
companies thought there

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:24.860
was a dollar to be made here.

00:14:24.860 --> 00:14:26.810
And a lot of that came from
Northern Africa or the Middle

00:14:26.810 --> 00:14:27.310
East.

00:14:27.310 --> 00:14:29.860
And I sort of dove back into it.

00:14:29.860 --> 00:14:31.270
There's your answer.

00:14:31.270 --> 00:14:31.810
Thank you.

00:14:31.810 --> 00:14:31.930
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Thank you.

00:14:31.930 --> 00:14:33.178
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:34.010 --> 00:14:35.470
I would love to
hear from the cast.

00:14:35.470 --> 00:14:40.180
Obviously, there's a very
diverse cast on stage with us.

00:14:40.180 --> 00:14:43.660
And I will ask you some
questions about representation,

00:14:43.660 --> 00:14:47.920
because I think that's a really
important thing that the show

00:14:47.920 --> 00:14:50.830
is bringing to Broadway.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:54.430
How did you all prepare for
your roles and prepare to--

00:14:54.430 --> 00:14:56.980
I mean, you're obviously
speaking in accents, many

00:14:56.980 --> 00:14:59.880
of you, that are not your own.

00:14:59.880 --> 00:15:01.810
You're working with a coach.

00:15:01.810 --> 00:15:03.310
What was the research
process like?

00:15:03.310 --> 00:15:08.210
And then, how did you
get into those roles?

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:10.580
DAVID CROMER: Everyone's
answer is very different.

00:15:10.580 --> 00:15:11.570
SHARONE SAYEGH: Yeah.

00:15:11.570 --> 00:15:13.940
So like Jonathan, my
family is also Israeli

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:15.899
and I grew up speaking
Hebrew at home.

00:15:15.899 --> 00:15:17.690
And I also grew up
speaking a little Arabic

00:15:17.690 --> 00:15:19.520
because my family
is Iraqi-Israeli.

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:22.370
So firstly, when I
found out about this,

00:15:22.370 --> 00:15:25.280
I was so excited because I
had never even auditioned

00:15:25.280 --> 00:15:27.620
for an Israeli
musical, you know?

00:15:27.620 --> 00:15:31.520
So I prepared a song in Hebrew,
which I was so excited to do,

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:32.730
for my audition.

00:15:32.730 --> 00:15:36.560
And specifically with my
character, I'm not this girl,

00:15:36.560 --> 00:15:40.580
but I very much know who
this girl in Israel is.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:42.632
And so I feel like
I've been doing

00:15:42.632 --> 00:15:44.840
the research for this girl
pretty much my whole life,

00:15:44.840 --> 00:15:45.830
I guess.

00:15:45.830 --> 00:15:49.520
But you know, I kind of
just tapped into my parents

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:52.580
accents, to be honest,
and my cousins' accents.

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:54.950
And that's how I prepared
for the audition.

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:55.450
Yeah.

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:57.033
DAVID CROMER: If I
could just toss in,

00:15:57.033 --> 00:15:59.570
the show is interesting
in that, like in the film,

00:15:59.570 --> 00:16:01.510
the Israelis tend
to speak Hebrew.

00:16:01.510 --> 00:16:02.870
The Egyptians speak Arabic.

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:05.150
And then they all
communicate with each other,

00:16:05.150 --> 00:16:08.277
struggling in English, which
is not anyone's first language.

00:16:08.277 --> 00:16:09.860
So it's all sort of
strangled English.

00:16:09.860 --> 00:16:11.457
You had pointed
out, at one point--

00:16:11.457 --> 00:16:13.040
you realized at one
point during tech,

00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:14.360
I speak no English in this show.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:15.210
I speak entirely Hebrew.

00:16:15.210 --> 00:16:15.590
SHARONE SAYEGH: Right.

00:16:15.590 --> 00:16:17.340
Which I actually didn't
realize until Bill

00:16:17.340 --> 00:16:18.417
pointed it out to me.

00:16:18.417 --> 00:16:20.500
And I was like, oh, all
of my lines are in Hebrew.

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:22.490
That's crazy.

00:16:22.490 --> 00:16:27.200
But it's very cool that I didn't
even realize that, actually.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:30.470
MICHAEL SHAYAN: George,
you are a violinist

00:16:30.470 --> 00:16:32.770
and you play classical
Arabic music.

00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:33.650
GEORGE ABUD: Yeah.

00:16:33.650 --> 00:16:36.170
MICHAEL SHAYAN:
Tell me about that.

00:16:36.170 --> 00:16:40.530
GEORGE ABUD: Well, I grew
up playing with my family.

00:16:40.530 --> 00:16:42.170
We're all musicians
in my family.

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:45.027
And I'm Lebanese, like Yazbek.

00:16:45.027 --> 00:16:46.460
Yay!

00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:50.150
And we all played Arabic
music together growing up,

00:16:50.150 --> 00:16:50.840
and it was--

00:16:50.840 --> 00:16:53.780
we played for weddings and
parties and family events.

00:16:53.780 --> 00:16:55.939
And I have two older
brothers who also play,

00:16:55.939 --> 00:16:57.980
and we were kind of like
a little traveling band.

00:16:57.980 --> 00:16:59.290
And so when I saw about this--

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:00.870
and now I'm an
actor in the city.

00:17:00.870 --> 00:17:04.069
And when I saw about this
musical, about an Arabic band,

00:17:04.069 --> 00:17:04.940
my head exploded.

00:17:04.940 --> 00:17:06.319
I was like, what the
hell are they going

00:17:06.319 --> 00:17:07.250
to do about an Arabic band?

00:17:07.250 --> 00:17:08.791
That thing's going
to close in a day.

00:17:08.791 --> 00:17:10.819
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:10.819 --> 00:17:12.660
Proved me wrong.

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:14.270
So I was like, I
got to get in that.

00:17:14.270 --> 00:17:19.579
And then just being part of this
group, where a lot of people

00:17:19.579 --> 00:17:21.950
play and we get to
play music together,

00:17:21.950 --> 00:17:23.805
and it comes out
of this man's mind.

00:17:23.805 --> 00:17:26.180
And to sidetrack-- because I
don't know what the hell I'm

00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:27.346
saying about myself anymore.

00:17:27.346 --> 00:17:28.612
I'll just talk about Yazbek.

00:17:28.612 --> 00:17:30.070
DAVID YAZBEK: Always
a good policy.

00:17:30.070 --> 00:17:30.606
GEORGE ABUD: Yeah, I think so.

00:17:30.606 --> 00:17:31.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:31.340 --> 00:17:33.812
What's wonderful about
Yazbek and his music

00:17:33.812 --> 00:17:35.270
is, now that I'm
thinking about it,

00:17:35.270 --> 00:17:39.290
I think he really approaches
his composition like an actor.

00:17:39.290 --> 00:17:40.450
He's not just trying--

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:42.059
for this show,
it's not like, oh,

00:17:42.059 --> 00:17:44.600
did you listen to Arabic music
and then write an Arabic song?

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:47.183
It's like, he didn't just try
to write Arabic music or Klezmer

00:17:47.183 --> 00:17:47.810
music.

00:17:47.810 --> 00:17:51.200
These are all parts of his
eclectic taste and his history,

00:17:51.200 --> 00:17:53.840
and the rich experiences
that make him a very

00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:56.090
unique and diverse individual.

00:17:56.090 --> 00:17:57.740
And through that,
I think he just

00:17:57.740 --> 00:18:00.240
tried to become
these characters,

00:18:00.240 --> 00:18:02.855
and what are they going to say?

00:18:02.855 --> 00:18:04.730
And then, how are they
going to talk and then

00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:05.910
what's their circumstances?

00:18:05.910 --> 00:18:08.930
And that's layered into
Arabic music coming out

00:18:08.930 --> 00:18:12.890
or Arabic instrumentation coming
out, or Klezmer type stuff,

00:18:12.890 --> 00:18:14.990
or a certain instrumentation
for a certain song.

00:18:14.990 --> 00:18:16.834
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:17.810 --> 00:18:21.429
He's a wonderful guy and I
respect no one on this stage

00:18:21.429 --> 00:18:22.720
as much-- no, I'm just kidding.

00:18:22.720 --> 00:18:24.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:24.770 --> 00:18:26.377
MICHAEL SHAYAN: You guys--

00:18:26.377 --> 00:18:27.710
GEORGE ABUD: But it's very true.

00:18:27.710 --> 00:18:30.624
He didn't-- because people are
like, oh, is the score Arabic?

00:18:30.624 --> 00:18:32.040
I'm like, the score
is not Arabic,

00:18:32.040 --> 00:18:35.570
but it's Yazbek and the
Arabic that he knows,

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:37.670
and the music that
he's opened himself

00:18:37.670 --> 00:18:39.570
up to translated through him.

00:18:39.570 --> 00:18:43.040
And that's what makes it
a really awesome musical,

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:46.241
and not just trying to
copy an Umm Kulthum concert

00:18:46.241 --> 00:18:47.240
and putting it on stage.

00:18:47.240 --> 00:18:48.500
And then we're like, oh,
what's the show about?

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:50.210
Well, we just put some Umm
Kulthum songs together.

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:51.450
It's like, that's
not interesting.

00:18:51.450 --> 00:18:53.408
It's interesting because
it's this man's score,

00:18:53.408 --> 00:18:54.658
and that's why it's authentic.

00:18:54.658 --> 00:18:55.491
DAVID CROMER: Right.

00:18:55.491 --> 00:18:56.750
One of the things the show--

00:18:56.750 --> 00:18:58.333
one of the themes
this show deals with

00:18:58.333 --> 00:19:01.850
is how people can relate
through music, and how you can,

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:03.740
if you're stuck for
something to talk about,

00:19:03.740 --> 00:19:05.270
music might be a
good conversation,

00:19:05.270 --> 00:19:07.200
or listening to music
or talking about things.

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:10.460
And the film touches on this.

00:19:10.460 --> 00:19:13.080
And then Itamar and Yazbek
really expanded on this.

00:19:13.080 --> 00:19:19.250
That in the show, they play
old American pop songs.

00:19:19.250 --> 00:19:20.690
They sing Gershwin.

00:19:20.690 --> 00:19:24.140
They sing-- you know,
the people are listening

00:19:24.140 --> 00:19:25.700
to-- there's the Klezmer music.

00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:30.104
So it's music that people
have-- that everyone has heard.

00:19:30.104 --> 00:19:30.770
Does that make--

00:19:30.770 --> 00:19:31.978
I'm not explaining that well.

00:19:31.978 --> 00:19:36.320
But there's influences
from all kinds of music

00:19:36.320 --> 00:19:38.487
because this is a
generation of people

00:19:38.487 --> 00:19:40.820
who have managed to hear
little bits and pieces of music

00:19:40.820 --> 00:19:42.380
from all over the world.

00:19:42.380 --> 00:19:44.747
So it's about a lot of things.

00:19:44.747 --> 00:19:46.580
DAVID YAZBEK: What are
the other songs we're

00:19:46.580 --> 00:19:48.630
going to be performing today?

00:19:48.630 --> 00:19:49.880
MICHAEL SHAYAN: "Umm Kulthum."

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:50.780
DAVID YAZBEK: And
what's the other one?

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:51.560
Oh, and "Answer Me."

00:19:51.560 --> 00:19:52.220
MICHAEL SHAYAN: And "Answer Me."

00:19:52.220 --> 00:19:53.230
Yeah.

00:19:53.230 --> 00:19:55.563
DAVID YAZBEK: I just wanted
to know, for segue purposes.

00:19:55.563 --> 00:19:56.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:58.430
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Smooth segues.

00:19:58.430 --> 00:19:59.791
And here's one right now.

00:19:59.791 --> 00:20:00.290
Katrina.

00:20:03.230 --> 00:20:05.750
So we talk a lot
about Umm Kulthum.

00:20:05.750 --> 00:20:09.170
Katrina, did you know
about Umm Kulthum

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:11.900
and was that part of
your research process?

00:20:11.900 --> 00:20:14.420
KATRINA LENK: I had not
heard of Umm Kulthum before.

00:20:14.420 --> 00:20:16.970
And of course, one must know.

00:20:16.970 --> 00:20:20.270
So I thank God for the internet.

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:22.055
There's a lot of
stuff you can find.

00:20:22.055 --> 00:20:23.180
DAVID CROMER: Did you use--

00:20:23.180 --> 00:20:24.600
KATRINA LENK: There's a lot of
things you don't want to find.

00:20:24.600 --> 00:20:25.370
But I used--

00:20:25.370 --> 00:20:25.990
DAVID CROMER: Did
you use Google?

00:20:25.990 --> 00:20:27.281
What search engine did you use?

00:20:27.281 --> 00:20:28.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:29.145 --> 00:20:30.770
KATRINA LENK: So I
have Google to thank

00:20:30.770 --> 00:20:35.519
for my knowledge of Umm Kulthum.

00:20:35.519 --> 00:20:37.685
MICHAEL SHAYAN: David, can
you give her another $20?

00:20:37.685 --> 00:20:40.342
KATRINA LENK: Hey, I think you
guys should maybe give me $20?

00:20:40.342 --> 00:20:42.008
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Sergei
can give her $20.

00:20:45.290 --> 00:20:46.320
KATRINA LENK: But she--

00:20:46.320 --> 00:20:47.960
and what am I saying?

00:20:47.960 --> 00:20:52.710
So yes, there's recordings
available on the internet.

00:20:52.710 --> 00:20:56.990
But also, I learned things from
George Abud, who, like he said,

00:20:56.990 --> 00:20:58.910
is really familiar
with Arabic music,

00:20:58.910 --> 00:21:01.580
and helped me understand
what I was hearing.

00:21:01.580 --> 00:21:05.570
Because it's such a different
way of expressing musicality

00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:09.140
than what we do in our Western--
and even in classical music,

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:10.820
what we consider
classical music.

00:21:10.820 --> 00:21:14.360
So that was really a
fascinating thing to learn,

00:21:14.360 --> 00:21:17.450
and I'm still learning
about all of the differences

00:21:17.450 --> 00:21:21.455
of Umm Kulthum's music.

00:21:21.455 --> 00:21:22.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:25.060
MICHAEL SHAYAN: And
you're actually,

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:26.893
I mean, in your last
show, "Indecent," which

00:21:26.893 --> 00:21:28.550
was on Broadway recently--

00:21:28.550 --> 00:21:29.050
yes.

00:21:29.050 --> 00:21:30.400
[APPLAUSE]

00:21:30.400 --> 00:21:31.290
You were incredible.

00:21:34.280 --> 00:21:35.734
You were playing violin.

00:21:35.734 --> 00:21:36.942
KATRINA LENK: It was a viola.

00:21:36.942 --> 00:21:37.942
MICHAEL SHAYAN: A viola.

00:21:37.942 --> 00:21:40.130
I'm sorry.

00:21:40.130 --> 00:21:43.640
I'm sure that would kind
of help you as you're, I

00:21:43.640 --> 00:21:44.890
mean, preparing for this role.

00:21:44.890 --> 00:21:48.080
And you guys actually did a song
recently together for Artists

00:21:48.080 --> 00:21:49.080
For Peace.

00:21:49.080 --> 00:21:49.830
KATRINA LENK: Yes.

00:21:49.830 --> 00:21:50.900
MICHAEL SHAYAN: For world peace.

00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:51.399
Yes.

00:21:51.399 --> 00:21:53.470
And you played and
you sang beautifully.

00:21:53.470 --> 00:21:54.470
KATRINA LENK: Thank you.

00:21:54.470 --> 00:21:56.303
MICHAEL SHAYAN: And how
did that come about?

00:21:56.303 --> 00:21:57.620
KATRINA LENK: Well, George--

00:21:57.620 --> 00:21:57.890
GEORGE ABUD: Well, it--

00:21:57.890 --> 00:21:58.556
KATRINA LENK: Well, Sharone--

00:21:58.556 --> 00:21:59.535
GEORGE ABUD: Well,
Sharone-- well.

00:21:59.535 --> 00:22:00.326
KATRINA LENK: Well.

00:22:00.326 --> 00:22:01.169
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:03.140 --> 00:22:05.156
GEORGE ABUD: Sharone,
talk about the wonderful--

00:22:05.156 --> 00:22:05.947
SHARONE SAYEGH: OK.

00:22:05.947 --> 00:22:09.960
So I love this charity called
Artists for World Peace.

00:22:09.960 --> 00:22:10.760
They're wonderful.

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:13.280
And I've been producing a
Broadway charity event for them

00:22:13.280 --> 00:22:15.170
every year, and this
was our seventh year.

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:17.155
And last year was
our first time we

00:22:17.155 --> 00:22:18.780
had some performers
from Broadway shows

00:22:18.780 --> 00:22:19.940
sing in other languages.

00:22:19.940 --> 00:22:22.590
And I was like, oh, this is so
great because it's world peace.

00:22:22.590 --> 00:22:23.690
So this year, I
asked a lot of people

00:22:23.690 --> 00:22:25.250
from "The Band's
Visit" to perform,

00:22:25.250 --> 00:22:27.020
and George and Katrina said
they wanted to sing something

00:22:27.020 --> 00:22:27.690
together in Arabic.

00:22:27.690 --> 00:22:29.939
And I said that would be
wonderful, that'd be perfect.

00:22:29.939 --> 00:22:30.710
So they did.

00:22:30.710 --> 00:22:31.460
GEORGE ABUD: Yeah.

00:22:31.460 --> 00:22:36.650
So we kind of joined forces
on this and really wanted to--

00:22:36.650 --> 00:22:38.960
and I listen to lots and
lots of Arabic music.

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:40.820
That's kind of all I
listen to-- and jazz.

00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:41.984
But I was listening--

00:22:41.984 --> 00:22:43.400
I heard this song,
where it's just

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:45.910
oud, which is the
predecessor of the guitar.

00:22:45.910 --> 00:22:47.960
It's the lute-like instrument.

00:22:47.960 --> 00:22:50.782
And it was just the
composer playing the oud,

00:22:50.782 --> 00:22:53.240
and he was teaching the singer
the songs, so they were kind

00:22:53.240 --> 00:22:54.620
of just noodling through it.

00:22:54.620 --> 00:22:57.240
And I thought that was a
lovely little back-and-forth,

00:22:57.240 --> 00:23:00.209
so I thought this would be
a good one to teach Katrina.

00:23:00.209 --> 00:23:02.750
We learned it together because
I didn't know the song either.

00:23:02.750 --> 00:23:04.666
DAVID YAZBEK: You'll be
doing yourself a favor

00:23:04.666 --> 00:23:08.840
to go on YouTube and look up
Katrina Lenk and George Abud

00:23:08.840 --> 00:23:09.530
and WHAB--

00:23:09.530 --> 00:23:11.750
W-H-A-B-- and you'll
get that link.

00:23:11.750 --> 00:23:14.360
And I've watched it
now eight or 10 times.

00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:15.110
It's so gorgeous.

00:23:15.110 --> 00:23:16.010
MICHAEL SHAYAN: It really is.

00:23:16.010 --> 00:23:17.426
DAVID YAZBEK: And
it has nothing--

00:23:17.426 --> 00:23:18.470
I didn't write the song.

