 KULTHUM AND OMAR SHARIF"]

00:27:43.278 --> 00:27:48.734
[APPLAUSE]

00:27:57.900 --> 00:28:00.450
That was beautiful, and that
is one of my favorite songs

00:28:00.450 --> 00:28:01.560
in the show.

00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:03.720
And before, we were
talking a little bit,

00:28:03.720 --> 00:28:06.120
I learned that it
was actually cut.

00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:07.879
It was cut in an
earlier iteration.

00:28:07.879 --> 00:28:08.670
Tell me about that.

00:28:10.754 --> 00:28:13.170
DAVID YAZBEK: I don't know
what the fuck we were thinking.

00:28:13.170 --> 00:28:14.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:16.517 --> 00:28:17.100
You know what?

00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:18.817
You have a better
memory than me.

00:28:18.817 --> 00:28:19.650
And you'll be funny.

00:28:19.650 --> 00:28:21.072
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:22.019 --> 00:28:23.727
ITAMAR MOSES: I begged
him not to cut it.

00:28:23.727 --> 00:28:25.160
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:25.160 --> 00:28:28.590
No, musicals are very
difficult. And one

00:28:28.590 --> 00:28:30.060
of the reasons
they're difficult is

00:28:30.060 --> 00:28:31.890
that, with a play--
if I'm writing a play,

00:28:31.890 --> 00:28:34.980
I can have five friends who
are good actors come over

00:28:34.980 --> 00:28:37.500
to my apartment and read
it cold on my couch,

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:39.960
and basically have an
understanding of what I've got.

00:28:39.960 --> 00:28:44.010
In a musical, you can't
do that because to see

00:28:44.010 --> 00:28:46.560
how all of the different pieces
of machinery work together,

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:48.954
you need a week for
everybody to learn the music,

00:28:48.954 --> 00:28:50.370
and you kind of
probably want them

00:28:50.370 --> 00:28:51.920
on their feet a little bit.

00:28:51.920 --> 00:28:53.980
So to get the flow
of the whole thing,

00:28:53.980 --> 00:28:55.890
you need tens of
thousands of dollars

00:28:55.890 --> 00:28:57.960
and a week of rehearsal.

00:28:57.960 --> 00:29:01.710
All of which is to say when
you're developing a musical,

00:29:01.710 --> 00:29:05.340
it'll be six months between
opportunities to do that.

00:29:05.340 --> 00:29:07.080
There's even union
rules about how often

00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:08.320
you're allowed to do that.

00:29:08.320 --> 00:29:11.100
So you're around the
table, kind of hearing it,

00:29:11.100 --> 00:29:14.190
and in that context, you can
be like, well, I don't know,

00:29:14.190 --> 00:29:15.360
are we bored here?

00:29:15.360 --> 00:29:16.080
Let's move on.

00:29:16.080 --> 00:29:17.970
Or actually, we don't
want a song from her,

00:29:17.970 --> 00:29:20.370
we want a song from him
about what he's feeling.

00:29:20.370 --> 00:29:25.699
And in a way, there's a maybe
apocryphal story about--

00:29:25.699 --> 00:29:27.240
maybe it's Stanislavski
or something,

00:29:27.240 --> 00:29:29.059
or some Russian
director who was asked,

00:29:29.059 --> 00:29:30.850
how long do you want
to rehearse this show?

00:29:30.850 --> 00:29:31.950
And he said, two years.

00:29:31.950 --> 00:29:32.970
And they said, you
can't have two years.

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:34.136
And he said, then two weeks.

00:29:34.136 --> 00:29:35.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:35.280 --> 00:29:37.350
The point being,
you don't want the--

00:29:37.350 --> 00:29:40.290
it's possible to have enough
time to sort of mess something

00:29:40.290 --> 00:29:40.899
up.

00:29:40.899 --> 00:29:42.982
DAVID YAZBEK: I imagine
that that's what happened.

00:29:42.982 --> 00:29:45.148
And let me just say one
quick thing, which is that--

00:29:45.148 --> 00:29:49.710
and this would be
a part of the talk

00:29:49.710 --> 00:29:54.480
that Google might pay me $25,000
to give the same crowd about

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:57.160
collaboration at Google.

00:29:57.160 --> 00:29:58.450
This is just a suggestion.

00:29:58.450 --> 00:30:00.116
And my fee is a little
higher than that.

00:30:00.116 --> 00:30:05.850
But we have collaborated,
first, Itamar and I, then

00:30:05.850 --> 00:30:08.340
the three of us, then all
of us have collaborated

00:30:08.340 --> 00:30:11.130
beautifully and very closely.

00:30:11.130 --> 00:30:12.850
You want to listen
to the other people.

00:30:12.850 --> 00:30:14.940
But there are times--

00:30:14.940 --> 00:30:17.620
I'm not blaming what I'm about
to say on either of these guys.

00:30:17.620 --> 00:30:19.370
But there are times when--

00:30:19.370 --> 00:30:22.920
because this happened a long
time ago in the process--

00:30:22.920 --> 00:30:27.470
when we had a different
person involved.

00:30:27.470 --> 00:30:31.780
And you can be
over-collaborative.

00:30:31.780 --> 00:30:34.830
You can say, oh, yeah,
OK, we can cut that song.

00:30:34.830 --> 00:30:37.225
Sort of to prove
that you have it

00:30:37.225 --> 00:30:39.600
in you to cut a song-- to the
cut a beautiful-- you know,

00:30:39.600 --> 00:30:40.440
your baby.

00:30:40.440 --> 00:30:42.680
Because that's what
it's all about.

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:45.281
You have to be willing
to sacrifice your babies.

00:30:45.281 --> 00:30:45.780
OK.

00:30:45.780 --> 00:30:48.566
Let's cut it.

00:30:48.566 --> 00:30:50.950
Then David Cromer
comes onto the project

00:30:50.950 --> 00:30:54.610
and he's like,
what is that song?

00:30:54.610 --> 00:30:55.930
Why isn't it in the show?

00:30:55.930 --> 00:30:56.890
Why did you cut it?

00:30:56.890 --> 00:30:58.110
You idiots.

00:30:58.110 --> 00:30:59.860
And it's sort of like,
yeah, you're right.

00:30:59.860 --> 00:31:00.390
We are idiots.

00:31:00.390 --> 00:31:01.306
It's a beautiful song.

00:31:01.306 --> 00:31:02.890
She sings it beautifully.

00:31:02.890 --> 00:31:05.350
So that's a little
lesson in collaboration.

00:31:05.350 --> 00:31:06.031
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:06.031 --> 00:31:07.780
DAVID CROMER: And the
specific facts of it

00:31:07.780 --> 00:31:12.100
are it was thought, for a while,
that at that point in the show,

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:15.710
we should hear from Tewfiq, the
character Tewfiq, in the scene.

00:31:15.710 --> 00:31:19.810
And then it was realized
that we would hear from her.

00:31:19.810 --> 00:31:23.180
And sometimes, something
like that's a coin flip.

00:31:23.180 --> 00:31:27.474
And we placed ourselves in the
path of a fortuitous accident.

00:31:27.474 --> 00:31:29.890
ITAMAR MOSES: Yeah, in a way,
a more practical and compact

00:31:29.890 --> 00:31:32.950
answer to the question is that
Katrina's character Dina sings

00:31:32.950 --> 00:31:35.260
four or five times over
the course of the show,

00:31:35.260 --> 00:31:37.240
and Tewfiq sings almost never.

00:31:37.240 --> 00:31:39.130
So we were sort of
thinking, surely

00:31:39.130 --> 00:31:41.579
we need to hear more from him.

00:31:41.579 --> 00:31:43.120
And not over and
over again from her.

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:45.310
And it turns out, that's wrong.

00:31:45.310 --> 00:31:47.500
You do want to hear her
sing again and again.

00:31:47.500 --> 00:31:49.420
DAVID YAZBEK: Yeah,
and that surely

00:31:49.420 --> 00:31:52.435
is the sound of the rule book.

00:31:52.435 --> 00:31:54.100
That to do a show
like this, you have

00:31:54.100 --> 00:31:57.470
to be ripping up constantly,
constantly, constantly.

00:31:57.470 --> 00:32:01.390
And if you're working at
Google, if you're coding or--

00:32:01.390 --> 00:32:01.890
sorry.

00:32:01.890 --> 00:32:02.931
DAVID CROMER: [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:02.931 --> 00:32:04.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:04.390 --> 00:32:07.812
MICHAEL SHAYAN: I
have $25,000 coming.

00:32:07.812 --> 00:32:09.270
I would love to
hear from the cast.

00:32:09.270 --> 00:32:13.510
So this show, before it hit
Broadway, was at the Atlantic.

00:32:13.510 --> 00:32:16.000
And many of you were actually
involved with that Atlantic

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:18.940
iteration, right?

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:20.460
And who was not involved?

00:32:20.460 --> 00:32:22.660
Who was not involved?

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:23.300
OK, cool.

00:32:23.300 --> 00:32:23.800
Right.

00:32:23.800 --> 00:32:25.360
Etai and Adam.

00:32:25.360 --> 00:32:27.840
So I would love to
hear from you guys.

00:32:27.840 --> 00:32:32.130
Just please introduce yourself,
the role that you're playing.

00:32:32.130 --> 00:32:35.980
What's it like interpreting
a role off-Broadway

00:32:35.980 --> 00:32:39.070
and then taking it
onto a bigger stage?

00:32:39.070 --> 00:32:42.902
How are you-- are you becoming
more aware of your movements?

00:32:42.902 --> 00:32:44.860
You're playing to a bigger
audience, obviously.

00:32:44.860 --> 00:32:48.260
What's that like for you?

00:32:48.260 --> 00:32:52.520
RACHEL PRATHER: My name's
Rachel Prather and I play Julia.

00:32:52.520 --> 00:32:54.630
As an actor, that's
a dream situation,

00:32:54.630 --> 00:32:57.860
especially in the time
frame that we were given.

00:32:57.860 --> 00:33:01.730
Because we got to do this show
in a very intimate setting

00:33:01.730 --> 00:33:04.400
off-broadway, 200-seat theater.

00:33:04.400 --> 00:33:07.820
And a pretty long rehearsal
process with table

00:33:07.820 --> 00:33:10.430
work and putting it on our feet.

00:33:10.430 --> 00:33:13.970
And then we took a break
for like nine months,

00:33:13.970 --> 00:33:16.070
and then we found out we
were going to Broadway.

00:33:16.070 --> 00:33:19.790
And so you have all of that
time for your characters

00:33:19.790 --> 00:33:23.360
to just sink in and do
more research on your own.

00:33:23.360 --> 00:33:26.839
And I loved having two
different iterations of the show

00:33:26.839 --> 00:33:28.130
and being part of both of them.

00:33:28.130 --> 00:33:29.730
It was really special.

00:33:29.730 --> 00:33:31.830
JOHN CARIANI: I'm
John and I play Itzik.

00:33:31.830 --> 00:33:33.290
And when I found out we
were going to Broadway,

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:34.040
I said, oh, great.

00:33:34.040 --> 00:33:36.140
My Hebrew will be
good and my accent

00:33:36.140 --> 00:33:39.710
won't be terrible because
when we were downtown,

00:33:39.710 --> 00:33:40.940
my accent wasn't very good.

00:33:40.940 --> 00:33:43.240
So it was very exciting
to get to revisit it.

00:33:43.240 --> 00:33:46.120
But it was great because we had
Etai and Sharone and Jonathan

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:47.300
to help us.

00:33:47.300 --> 00:33:49.700
And it was also fun to
just do it in a big space

00:33:49.700 --> 00:33:51.340
because the Atlantic
was really small.

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:53.840
And I remember David came up
to me one day and he said, see,

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:55.160
now you can lean
back on the couch

00:33:55.160 --> 00:33:56.368
because we're in a big space.

00:33:56.368 --> 00:33:56.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:56.890 --> 00:33:58.056
So that was really exciting.

00:34:00.740 --> 00:34:04.310
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Is it
hard to sing in an accent?

00:34:04.310 --> 00:34:05.900
Is that challenging
for you guys?

00:34:05.900 --> 00:34:06.995
JOHN CARIANI: You
should talk about that.

00:34:06.995 --> 00:34:07.870
ARI'EL STACHEL: Yeah.

00:34:09.674 --> 00:34:12.590
It is challenging.

00:34:12.590 --> 00:34:14.480
I think the most
challenging part about it,

00:34:14.480 --> 00:34:18.199
though, is that we learn
through the process

00:34:18.199 --> 00:34:20.120
that some things could
not be understood

00:34:20.120 --> 00:34:21.530
if I was singing
it in the accent

00:34:21.530 --> 00:34:22.613
that I was speaking it in.

00:34:22.613 --> 00:34:26.300
So we were literally
negotiating each and every vowel

00:34:26.300 --> 00:34:26.989
and consonant.

00:34:26.989 --> 00:34:29.840
So this [ROLLING "R"] is a
[ROLLING "R"] and this one is

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:31.710
[HARD "R"],, and this
one we're tapping.

00:34:31.710 --> 00:34:36.199
And so that is, I
think, not even-- we're

00:34:36.199 --> 00:34:37.909
not talking about
singing in an accent.

00:34:37.909 --> 00:34:39.034
That's a whole other thing.

00:34:39.034 --> 00:34:41.179
But it's a really
interesting negotiation

00:34:41.179 --> 00:34:46.489
to speak in a dialect and then
figure out how, in song, you

00:34:46.489 --> 00:34:48.800
can be understood and still
give sort of the flair

00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:50.870
and essence of the dialect.

00:34:50.870 --> 00:34:52.130
Yeah, it's a lot of work.

00:34:52.130 --> 00:34:54.054
It took a lot of work.

00:34:54.054 --> 00:34:55.429
MICHAEL SHAYAN:
Yeah, and Andrew,

00:34:55.429 --> 00:34:58.850
I learned that your
wife is actually

00:34:58.850 --> 00:35:01.370
involved in the production
as a dialect coach

00:35:01.370 --> 00:35:03.759
and I think you
said a dramaturg.

00:35:03.759 --> 00:35:04.550
ANDREW POLK: Right.

00:35:04.550 --> 00:35:04.790
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Yeah.

00:35:04.790 --> 00:35:06.600
What's it like working
with your wife?

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:08.540
ANDREW POLK: I live
with the dialect coach.

00:35:08.540 --> 00:35:10.670
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:10.670 --> 00:35:11.715
So I got a lot of notes.

00:35:11.715 --> 00:35:13.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:13.960 --> 00:35:16.061
And she's Israeli.

00:35:16.061 --> 00:35:16.560
I'm not.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:18.740
And so it was also
helpful, in terms

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:21.920
of the context of the play.

00:35:21.920 --> 00:35:23.410
I learned a lot from her.

00:35:23.410 --> 00:35:25.310
Obviously, we all did.

00:35:25.310 --> 00:35:28.160
The Israelis, with our accents.

00:35:28.160 --> 00:35:32.300
But also, I have been
immersed in Israeli culture

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:34.460
by the marriage choice I made.

00:35:34.460 --> 00:35:37.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:37.364 --> 00:35:38.780
JOHN CARIANI: The
best was the way

00:35:38.780 --> 00:35:41.360
she gave him dialect
notes and the way she gave

00:35:41.360 --> 00:35:43.010
the rest of us dialect notes.

00:35:43.010 --> 00:35:45.020
She was so kind and polite
and cheerful with us

00:35:45.020 --> 00:35:46.353
and she was kind of hard on him.

00:35:46.353 --> 00:35:47.000
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:47.780
ANDREW POLK: Yeah, she was.

00:35:47.780 --> 00:35:49.946
She was like-- she was, and
she'd come to me and say

00:35:49.946 --> 00:35:51.530
[NON-ENGLISH].

00:35:51.530 --> 00:35:53.611
No, [NON-ENGLISH].

00:35:53.611 --> 00:35:54.110
All right.

00:35:54.110 --> 00:35:55.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:55.130 --> 00:35:57.150
Better go home.

00:35:57.150 --> 00:35:59.595
So that's what happened.

00:35:59.595 --> 00:36:00.470
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Yeah.

