So please line up at
the mics on either side.

00:36:07.525 --> 00:36:08.900
And we have a
question over here.

00:36:08.900 --> 00:36:10.190
AUDIENCE: First of all,
thank you so much for coming,

00:36:10.190 --> 00:36:10.760
and very impressive.

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:12.200
If you didn't grow up
saying [INAUDIBLE],,

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:13.790
to be able to do it, I
give you a lot of credit.

00:36:13.790 --> 00:36:14.630
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:15.740 --> 00:36:17.740
You guys all
collaborate beautifully,

00:36:17.740 --> 00:36:21.460
but obviously, there's a lot
of underlying political tones

00:36:21.460 --> 00:36:24.080
about the story and the message.

00:36:24.080 --> 00:36:26.990
I'm wondering what it meant to
some of you to be part of it,

00:36:26.990 --> 00:36:29.790
especially if you grew
up Israeli or Lebanese,

00:36:29.790 --> 00:36:33.170
and what it meant to
bring together onstage.

00:36:33.170 --> 00:36:34.440
Was it difficult?

00:36:34.440 --> 00:36:36.090
How your families felt about it?

00:36:36.090 --> 00:36:37.584
So just curious to
hear about that.

00:36:37.584 --> 00:36:39.750
ARI'EL STACHEL: I have a
lot of opinions about that.

00:36:39.750 --> 00:36:42.720
It's really, really,
really complicated.

00:36:42.720 --> 00:36:45.780
I mean, first, you asked
about representation.

00:36:45.780 --> 00:36:47.880
I mean, on the first
level, those of us

00:36:47.880 --> 00:36:51.060
in the cast who come from
Middle Eastern backgrounds,

00:36:51.060 --> 00:36:53.760
there was so much sort of
self-inflicted pressure

00:36:53.760 --> 00:36:54.660
to get this job.

00:36:54.660 --> 00:36:57.570
Because this felt like our
ticket to have a thing.

00:36:57.570 --> 00:36:58.560
So there's that.

00:36:58.560 --> 00:37:00.004
But the other thing that's--

00:37:00.004 --> 00:37:01.920
DAVID YAZBEK: How many
times did you audition?

00:37:01.920 --> 00:37:02.836
ARI'EL STACHEL: Seven.

00:37:02.836 --> 00:37:04.364
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:04.364 --> 00:37:06.030
ITAMAR MOSES: The
last three were just--

00:37:06.030 --> 00:37:07.700
DAVID CROMER: That seventh
audition wasn't for real.

00:37:07.700 --> 00:37:07.910
ITAMAR MOSES: Yeah.

00:37:07.910 --> 00:37:08.560
We were just kidding.

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:10.393
ARI'EL STACHEL: Seven
auditions for the kid.

00:37:10.393 --> 00:37:12.080
No, and I think--

00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:14.880
but it's also really
interesting to sort of, I think,

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:16.860
understand ourselves
in this identity.

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:20.010
Because I, for
example, am the son

00:37:20.010 --> 00:37:23.760
of a Yemenite-Israeli father,
so I'm Jewish and Israeli,

00:37:23.760 --> 00:37:27.870
but also my family practices
a lot of Arab traditions.

00:37:27.870 --> 00:37:30.212
And I've always
felt like, at least

00:37:30.212 --> 00:37:31.920
as I've entered the
business in New York,

00:37:31.920 --> 00:37:36.150
like I have this birthright to
play Middle Eastern characters.

00:37:36.150 --> 00:37:39.060
But I think, as
we play this, I'm

00:37:39.060 --> 00:37:41.310
starting to realize all of
the nuance that's needed.

00:37:41.310 --> 00:37:43.710
And I don't really know
what I'm saying anymore,

00:37:43.710 --> 00:37:46.800
other than the fact
that it's lovely to take

00:37:46.800 --> 00:37:48.864
on this other culture,
and I'm learning a lot.

00:37:48.864 --> 00:37:50.280
And there's this
beautiful drummer

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:53.490
in the cast named Ossama Farouk,
who's been extremely helpful,

00:37:53.490 --> 00:37:57.200
who's Alexandrian.

00:37:57.200 --> 00:38:00.960
But I think it means a lot
to many of us, personally.

00:38:00.960 --> 00:38:04.740
It means a huge amount to me
to be able to play this role,

00:38:04.740 --> 00:38:06.990
and it not really
being political at all.

00:38:06.990 --> 00:38:10.860
It allows me to understand
myself as a Yemenite-Israeli

00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:13.470
Middle Eastern American
man differently,

00:38:13.470 --> 00:38:15.360
and more confidently.

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:18.420
ITAMAR MOSES: Yeah,
I mean, just--

00:38:18.420 --> 00:38:20.740
yeah, and I definitely want
to hear more from you guys.

00:38:20.740 --> 00:38:22.957
Because we-- I don't know.

00:38:22.957 --> 00:38:25.290
I'm curious how it-- actually,
how it feels for you guys

00:38:25.290 --> 00:38:26.570
after running it for so long.

00:38:26.570 --> 00:38:28.320
Because we had one
answer to this question

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:30.300
when we were rehearsing it,
but now it's been theirs.

00:38:30.300 --> 00:38:31.440
It's been entirely
in their hands,

00:38:31.440 --> 00:38:33.510
dealing with meeting
people at the stage door

00:38:33.510 --> 00:38:35.080
and how people are reacting.

00:38:35.080 --> 00:38:36.942
But I know that
us, going into it--

00:38:36.942 --> 00:38:38.400
and it's one of
the reasons I think

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:42.246
the movie is so successful.

00:38:42.246 --> 00:38:45.720
It's not that it's apolitical
or that it avoids politics.

00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:48.480
It makes this enormously
political statement

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:56.970
by demonstrating that when
you strip away the things

00:38:56.970 --> 00:38:59.160
that we normally see in
headlines about the region--

00:38:59.160 --> 00:39:02.380
rhetoric from leaders,
disputes over borders.

00:39:02.380 --> 00:39:06.570
This is one group of people
that needs food and a roof,

00:39:06.570 --> 00:39:08.670
and another group of people
that has those things.

00:39:08.670 --> 00:39:11.460
And when everything
else is stripped away,

00:39:11.460 --> 00:39:16.770
it's about those basic
human needs, and things

00:39:16.770 --> 00:39:18.540
over which you can connect.

00:39:18.540 --> 00:39:21.002
So there's something--
it's not that it's not

00:39:21.002 --> 00:39:22.210
making a political statement.

00:39:22.210 --> 00:39:24.084
It's that the political
statement it's making

00:39:24.084 --> 00:39:27.360
is that there are elemental
human things beyond politics.

00:39:27.360 --> 00:39:32.250
And I think that's why it
was such a hit as a film when

00:39:32.250 --> 00:39:33.840
it was released in
Israel, and I think

00:39:33.840 --> 00:39:36.390
it's kind of how
it's operating here.

00:39:36.390 --> 00:39:39.000
But I want to hear
more from you guys.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:40.950
ETAI BENSON: I've heard
from so many people--

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:44.169
my family is also Israeli, and
a lot of Israeli Middle Eastern

00:39:44.169 --> 00:39:46.710
people at the stage door will
say that they were so refreshed

00:39:46.710 --> 00:39:48.900
that it wasn't--

00:39:48.900 --> 00:39:51.210
no politics were
sledgehammered down

00:39:51.210 --> 00:39:54.090
the throats of the audience.

00:39:54.090 --> 00:39:57.420
It's a very human story
that could, honestly,

00:39:57.420 --> 00:39:59.110
take place anywhere.

00:39:59.110 --> 00:40:01.200
It just-- we happen to
look at it through the lens

00:40:01.200 --> 00:40:01.991
of the Middle East.

00:40:01.991 --> 00:40:03.560
There's a moment in the film--

00:40:03.560 --> 00:40:07.200
Itamar, you've talked
about this a lot--

00:40:07.200 --> 00:40:09.480
when the Egyptian
band arrives and they

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:11.100
sit at the cafe to eat.

00:40:11.100 --> 00:40:15.150
There's a photograph
on the wall of a tank,

00:40:15.150 --> 00:40:16.897
and possibly from
the Yom Kippur War.

00:40:16.897 --> 00:40:17.730
I'm not really sure.

00:40:17.730 --> 00:40:19.110
You just kind of get
a quick glimpse of it.

00:40:19.110 --> 00:40:21.150
And one of the band
members takes his hat off

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:23.280
and just hangs it
right over the photo,

00:40:23.280 --> 00:40:24.690
and the photo is covered.

00:40:24.690 --> 00:40:27.240
And that kind of just
sets the tone for the film

00:40:27.240 --> 00:40:30.030
and that's the tone
of our show, too.

00:40:30.030 --> 00:40:31.560
It's all underneath.

00:40:31.560 --> 00:40:35.450
All the political tensions that
we all know about are there,

00:40:35.450 --> 00:40:40.980
but we're choosing, in our show,
to set those aside for now.

00:40:40.980 --> 00:40:45.090
And I think that sentiment
transfers beautifully

00:40:45.090 --> 00:40:47.000
to the play from the film.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.460
SHARONE SAYEGH: And just also
from the actor's perspective,

00:40:50.460 --> 00:40:52.930
being a Middle Eastern
actor in the city,

00:40:52.930 --> 00:40:54.780
auditioning for
other shows and TV

00:40:54.780 --> 00:40:57.540
shows and whatnot
up until this point,

00:40:57.540 --> 00:41:01.071
it gets really exhausting
to play the same thing over

00:41:01.071 --> 00:41:01.570
and over.

00:41:01.570 --> 00:41:04.297
It's just this very
stereotypical idea

00:41:04.297 --> 00:41:05.880
of what the region
is, and it's always

00:41:05.880 --> 00:41:08.310
about politics and
war and terrorism.

00:41:08.310 --> 00:41:12.095
And it's like, this
show is about people.

00:41:12.095 --> 00:41:13.470
It's just about
people who happen

00:41:13.470 --> 00:41:14.610
to live in the Middle East.

00:41:14.610 --> 00:41:16.890
And these people are not
defined by the politics

00:41:16.890 --> 00:41:18.450
of their government.

00:41:18.450 --> 00:41:23.190
They have their own
ideas, their own stories.

00:41:23.190 --> 00:41:25.270
So the fact that it's a
Middle Eastern musical

00:41:25.270 --> 00:41:28.230
and I wasn't auditioning for
terrorist wife number three

00:41:28.230 --> 00:41:30.480
was really, really
refreshing and wonderful.

00:41:30.480 --> 00:41:33.034
So I feel very grateful to
be a part of this story.

00:41:33.034 --> 00:41:34.200
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:34.943
Your answers are beautiful.

00:41:34.943 --> 00:41:35.480
ADAM KANTOR: And I think what--

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:35.750
AUDIENCE: Oh, please.

00:41:35.750 --> 00:41:35.810
Sorry.

00:41:35.810 --> 00:41:37.670
ADAM KANTOR: I was just going to
say, what moves me as an Amer--

00:41:37.670 --> 00:41:38.090
I'm not Israeli.

00:41:38.090 --> 00:41:39.089
My family's not Israeli.

00:41:39.089 --> 00:41:45.920
But what moves me as an American
doing this piece, in America,

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:48.230
in an American
theater with Americans

00:41:48.230 --> 00:41:51.680
is telling a story about
two groups of people

00:41:51.680 --> 00:41:56.990
from very different backgrounds
with very different ideologies

00:41:56.990 --> 00:42:00.659
coming together and just
being together for a night.

00:42:00.659 --> 00:42:02.950
MICHAEL SHAYAN: I was excited
to hear that a lot of you

00:42:02.950 --> 00:42:06.520
actually took a trip
together to Israel.

00:42:06.520 --> 00:42:08.749
What was that like?

00:42:08.749 --> 00:42:09.540
ITAMAR MOSES: Yeah.

00:42:09.540 --> 00:42:12.877
I mean, I'd been there because
I have family there also,

00:42:12.877 --> 00:42:13.960
and I'd been there before.

00:42:13.960 --> 00:42:16.043
But yes, between the
off-Broadway and the Broadway

00:42:16.043 --> 00:42:19.530
productions, Yazbek and
Cromer and Katrina and Ari'el

00:42:19.530 --> 00:42:22.230
was there and George was there.

00:42:22.230 --> 00:42:25.230
We went for a few
days to Israel.

00:42:25.230 --> 00:42:27.430
And specifically, we
went to [NON-ENGLISH],,

00:42:27.430 --> 00:42:30.750
which is the town in the
desert where Eran Kolirin

00:42:30.750 --> 00:42:32.690
and the filmmaker
filmed the movie.

00:42:32.690 --> 00:42:34.590
So Bet Hatikva is
fictional, but it's

00:42:34.590 --> 00:42:38.940
based on this little village
in the middle of nowhere.

00:42:38.940 --> 00:42:43.304
And it was sort of
profound to go there,

00:42:43.304 --> 00:42:45.720
not just to see the locations
from the movie that we knew.

00:42:45.720 --> 00:42:50.610
But to feel the isolation
and the vastness

00:42:50.610 --> 00:42:53.640
of the desert around you
was really something.

00:42:53.640 --> 00:42:54.960
KATRINA LENK: Yeah.

00:42:54.960 --> 00:42:58.080
We stood outside in the desert
for what felt like hours,

00:42:58.080 --> 00:42:59.791
just listening to the wind.

00:42:59.791 --> 00:43:01.790
And I'd be like, you guys,
can we go on the bus?

00:43:01.790 --> 00:43:02.280
It's hot.

00:43:02.280 --> 00:43:02.779
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:02.779 --> 00:43:06.270
But that sound of
just wind coming from

00:43:06.270 --> 00:43:07.530
someplace you can't explain.

00:43:07.530 --> 00:43:09.210
Because there's nothing for
it to bounce off-- like,

00:43:09.210 --> 00:43:10.270
where's it coming from?

00:43:10.270 --> 00:43:12.030
But it's like,
whah, in your ears.

00:43:12.030 --> 00:43:14.310
And sun and the sky--

00:43:14.310 --> 00:43:19.056
just getting to experience
that was really extraordinary.

00:43:19.056 --> 00:43:20.340
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Oh, wow.

00:43:20.340 --> 00:43:20.840
OK.

00:43:20.840 --> 00:43:24.060
We're going to close out with
a song, but before we do,

00:43:24.060 --> 00:43:28.560
I want to play a quick game.

00:43:28.560 --> 00:43:30.050
So this is a parlor game.

00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:34.532
It was popularized by
Marcel Proust in the 1880s.

00:43:34.532 --> 00:43:35.990
And the whole point
of it is to get

00:43:35.990 --> 00:43:39.240
to know the answerers
on a deeper level.

00:43:39.240 --> 00:43:40.605
So you guys down for a game?

00:43:40.605 --> 00:43:41.480
SHARONE SAYEGH: Yeah.

00:43:41.480 --> 00:43:43.070
MICHAEL SHAYAN: Great.

